# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: maximum-demand-indicator
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/base-load] The **base load** (also **baseload**) is the minimum level of demand on an electrical grid over a span of time, for example, one week.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/base-load] This demand can be met by unvarying power plants or dispatchable generation, depending on which approach has the best mix of cost, availability and reliability in any particular market.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/base-load] The remainder of demand, varying throughout a day, is met by intermittent sources together with dispatchable generation (such as load following power plants, peaking power plants, which can be turned up or down quickly) or energy storage.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/base-load] Power plants that do not change their power output quickly, such as some large coal or nuclear plants, are generally called **baseload power plants**.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/base-load] In the 20th century most or all of base load demand was met with baseload power plants, whereas new capacity based around renewables often employs flexible generation.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/base-load] Grid operators take long and short term bids to provide electricity over various time periods and balance supply and demand continuously.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/base-load] The detailed adjustments are known as the unit commitment problem in electrical power production.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/base-load] While historically large power grids used unvarying power plants to meet the base load, there is no specific technical requirement for this to be so.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/base-load] The base load can equally well be met by the appropriate quantity of intermittent power sources and dispatchable generation.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/base-load] Unvarying power plants can be coal, nuclear, combined cycle plants, which may take several days to start up and shut down, hydroelectric, geothermal, biogas, and biomass.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/base-load] The desirable attribute of dispatchability applies to some gas plants and hydroelectricity.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/base-load] Grid operators also use *curtailment* to shut plants out of the grid when their energy is not needed.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/base-load] Grid operators solicit bids to find the cheapest sources of electricity over short and long term buying periods.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/base-load] Traditionally, nuclear and coal plants had high fixed costs, high plant load factor but low marginal costs.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/base-load] On the other hand, peak load generators, such as natural gas, had low fixed costs, low plant load factor and high marginal costs.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/base-load] The IEA has suggested that coal power plants should not run as baseload, because that emits a lot of carbon dioxide, which causes climate change.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/base-load] Some nuclear power stations, such as those in France, are physically capable of being used as load following power plants and do alter their output, to some degree, to help meet varying demands.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/base-load] Some combined-cycle plants usually fuelled by gas, can provide baseload power, as well as being able to be cost-effectively cycled up and down to match more rapid fluctuations in consumption.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/base-load] According to National Grid plc chief executive officer Steve Holliday in 2015, and others, baseload is "outdated".
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/base-load] By 2019, Steve Holliday had left his position as CEO of National Grid plc and went on the record to say that, "It’s hard to conceive that nuclear does not have an important role to play".
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electrical-energy] Electrical energy is usually sold by the kilowatt-hour (1 kW·h = 3.6 MJ) which is the product of the power in kilowatts multiplied by running time in hours.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electrical-energy] Electric utilities measure energy using an electricity meter, which keeps a running total of the electrical energy delivered to a customer.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electrical-energy] Electric heating is an example of converting electrical energy into thermal energy.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electrical-energy] The simplest and most common type of electric heater uses electrical resistance to convert the energy.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electrical-energy] There are other ways to use electrical energy.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electrical-energy] Electric charges moves as a current the heater element which has a potential difference between the ends: energy is transferred from the charges to the element, increasing the element's temperature and thermal energy as the charges lose potential energy.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electrical-energy] Electricity generation is the process of generating electrical energy from other forms of energy.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electrical-energy] The fundamental principle of electricity generation was discovered during the 1820s and early 1830s by the British scientist Michael Faraday.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electrical-energy] His basic method is still used today: electric current is generated by the movement of a loop of wire, or disc of copper between the poles of a magnet.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electrical-energy] For electrical utilities, it is the first step in the delivery of electricity to consumers.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electrical-energy] The other processes, electricity transmission, distribution, and electrical energy storage and recovery using pumped-storage methods are normally carried out by the electric power industry.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electrical-energy] Electricity is most often generated at a power station by electromechanical generators, primarily driven by heat engines fueled by chemical combustion or nuclear fission but also by other means such as the kinetic energy of flowing water and wind.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electrical-energy] There are many other technologies that can be and are used to generate electricity such as solar photovoltaics and geothermal power.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] An **electricity meter**, **electric meter**, **electrical meter**, **energy meter**, **kilowatt-hour meter**, or **power meter** is a device that measures the amount of electric energy consumed by a residence, a business, or an electrically powered device over a time interval.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Electric utilities use electric meters installed at customers' premises for billing and monitoring purposes.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] They are typically calibrated in billing units, the most common one being the kilowatt hour (*kWh*).
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] They are usually read once each billing period.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] When energy savings during certain periods are desired, some meters may measure demand, the maximum use of power in some interval.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] "Time of day" metering allows electric rates to be changed during a day, to record usage during peak high-cost periods and off-peak, lower-cost, periods.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Also, in some areas meters have relays for demand response load shedding during peak load periods.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The earliest commercial uses of electric energy, in the 1880s, had easily predictable usage; billing was based on the number of lamps or motors installed in a building.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] However, as usage spread, and especially with the invention of pluggable appliances, it also became more variable, and the electric utilities sought a means to bill customers based on actual rather than estimated usage.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Many experimental types of meter were developed.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Thomas Edison at first worked on a direct current (DC) electromechanical meter with a direct reading register, but instead developed an electrochemical metering system, which used an electrolytic cell to totalise current consumption.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] At periodic intervals the plates were removed and weighed, and the customer billed.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The electrochemical meter was labor-intensive to read and not well received by customers.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] DC meters often measured charge in ampere hours.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Since the voltage of the supply should remain substantially constant, the reading of the meter was proportional to actual energy consumed.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] For example, if a meter recorded that 100 ampere hours had been consumed on a 200-volt supply, then 20 kilowatt-hours of energy had been supplied.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In 1885 Ferranti offered a mercury motor meter with a register similar to gas meters; this had the advantage that the consumer could easily read the meter and verify consumption.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Another early electromagnetic meter with visible readouts was a DC meter by Hermann Aron, who patented it in 1884.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Hugo Hirst of the British General Electric Company introduced it commercially into Great Britain from 1888.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Aron's power meter (later adapted for AC power) recorded the total charge used over time, and showed it on a series of clock dials.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Electrochemical meters were also improved to be directly read out, such as the *Bastian electrolytic meter* invented in 1897, and the *Wright electrolytic meter* or *'Reason' meter* which was patented in 1900.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The Wright meter, used mainly in the United Kingdom, consisted of a vertically mounted glass structure with a mercury reservoir at the top of the meter.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] As current was drawn from the supply, electrochemical action transferred the mercury to the bottom of the column.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The height of the mercury indicated the total charge.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The meter had to be reset to zero before the reserve of mercury ran out.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Reset was performed by inverting the meter, restoring the mercury to the reservoir.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] These were the first alternating-current watt-hour meters, known by the name of Bláthy-meters.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The AC kilowatt hour meters used at present operate on the same principle as Bláthy's original invention.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Also around 1889, Elihu Thomson of the American General Electric company developed a recording watt meter (watt-hour meter) based on an ironless commutator motor.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] This meter overcame the disadvantages of the electrochemical type and could operate on either alternating or direct current.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The Bláthy meter was similar to Shallenberger and Thomson meter in that they are two-phase motor meter.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Although the induction meter would only work on alternating current, it eliminated the delicate and troublesome commutator of the Thomson design.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Shallenberger fell ill and was unable to refine his initial large and heavy design, although he did also develop a polyphase version.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In 1902, William Morris Mordey and Guy Carey Fricker patented the Mordey-Fricker electricity meter, which operated on a different principle from motor-type meters, using a clock mechanism whose balance wheel oscillated at a rate directly proportional to the current.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] It was suitable for both direct and alternating current without frequency error, and was designed for small domestic installations of twelve to thirty lamps.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The most common unit of measurement on the electricity meter is the kilowatt hour [*kWh*], which is equal to the amount of energy used by a load of one kilowatt over a period of one hour, or 3,600,000 joules.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Some electricity companies use the SI megajoule instead.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Demand is normally measured in watts, but averaged over a period, most often a quarter- or half-hour.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Reactive power is measured in "thousands of volt-ampere reactive-hours", (kvarh).
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] By convention, a "lagging" or inductive load, such as a motor, will have positive reactive power.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] A "leading", or capacitive load, will have negative reactive power.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Volt-amperes measures all power passed through a distribution network, including reactive and actual.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] This is equal to the product of root-mean-square volts and amperes.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Distortion of the electric current by loads is measured in several ways.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Power factor is the ratio of resistive (or real) power to volt-amperes.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] A capacitive load has a leading power factor, and an inductive load has a lagging power factor.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] A purely resistive load (such as a filament lamp, heater or kettle) exhibits a power factor of 1.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Current harmonics are a measure of distortion of the wave form.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] For example, electronic loads such as computer power supplies draw their current at the voltage peak to fill their internal storage elements.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] This can lead to a significant voltage drop near the supply voltage peak which shows as a flattening of the voltage waveform.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] This flattening causes odd harmonics which are not permissible if they exceed specific limits, as they are not only wasteful, but may interfere with the operation of other equipment.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Harmonic emissions are mandated by law in EU and other countries to fall within specified limits.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In addition to metering based on the amount of energy used, other types of metering are available.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Meters which measured the amount of charge (coulombs) used, known as ampere hour meters, were used in the early days of electrification.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] These were dependent upon the supply voltage remaining constant for accurate measurement of energy usage, which was not a likely circumstance with most supplies.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The most common application was in relation to special-purpose meters to monitor charge / discharge status of large batteries.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Some meters measured only the length of time for which charge flowed, with no measurement of the magnitude of voltage or current being made.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] These are only suited for constant-load applications and are rarely used today.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Electricity meters operate by continuously measuring the instantaneous voltage (volts) and current (amperes) to give energy used (in joules, kilowatt-hours etc.).
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Meters for smaller services (such as small residential customers) can be connected directly in-line between source and customer.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] For larger loads, more than about 200 ampere of load, current transformers are used, so that the meter can be located somewhere other than in line with the service conductors.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The meters fall into two basic categories, electromechanical and electronic.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The most common type of electricity meter is the electromechanical watt-hour meter.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] On a single-phase AC supply, the electromechanical induction meter operates through electromagnetic induction by counting the revolutions of a non-magnetic, but electrically conductive, metal disc which is made to rotate at a speed proportional to the power passing through the meter.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The number of revolutions is thus proportional to the energy usage.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The voltage coil consumes a small and relatively constant amount of power, typically around 2 watts which is not registered on the meter.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The current coil similarly consumes a small amount of power in proportion to the square of the current flowing through it, typically up to a couple of watts at full load, which is registered on the meter.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The disc is acted upon by two sets of induction coils, which form, in effect, a two phase linear induction motor.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] One coil is connected in such a way that it produces a magnetic flux in proportion to the voltage and the other produces a magnetic flux in proportion to the current.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The field of the voltage coil is delayed by 90 degrees, due to the coil's inductive nature, and calibrated using a lag coil.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] This produces eddy currents in the disc and the effect is such that a force is exerted on the disc in proportion to the product of the instantaneous current and instantaneous voltage.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] A permanent magnet acts as an eddy current brake, exerting an opposing force proportional to the speed of rotation of the disc.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The equilibrium between these two opposing forces results in the disc rotating at a speed proportional to the power or rate of energy usage.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The disc drives a register mechanism which counts revolutions, much like the odometer in a car, in order to render a measurement of the total energy used.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Different phase configurations use additional voltage and current coils.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The disc is supported by a spindle which has a worm gear which drives the register.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The register is a series of dials which record the amount of energy used.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The dials may be of the *cyclometer* type, an odometer-like display that is easy to read where for each dial a single digit is shown through a window in the face of the meter, or of the pointer type where a pointer indicates each digit.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] With the dial pointer type, adjacent pointers generally rotate in opposite directions due to the gearing mechanism.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The amount of energy represented by one revolution of the disc is denoted by the symbol Kh which is given in units of watt-hours per revolution.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Using the value of Kh one can determine their power consumption at any given time by timing the disc with a stopwatch.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] For example, if *Kh* = 7.2 as above, and one revolution took place in 14.4 seconds, the power is 1800 watts.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] This method can be used to determine the power consumption of household devices by switching them on one by one.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Most domestic electricity meters must be read manually, whether by a representative of the power company or by the customer.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Where the customer reads the meter, the reading may be supplied to the power company by telephone, post or over the internet.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The electricity company will normally require a visit by a company representative at least annually in order to verify customer-supplied readings and to make a basic safety check of the meter.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In an induction type meter, creep is a phenomenon that can adversely affect accuracy, that occurs when the meter disc rotates continuously with potential applied and the load terminals open circuited.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] A test for error due to creep is called a creep test.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Two standards govern meter accuracy, ANSI C12.20 for North America and IEC 62053.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Electronic meters display the energy used on an LCD or LED display, and some can also transmit readings to remote places.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In addition to measuring energy used, some electronic meters can also record other parameters of the load and supply such as instantaneous and maximum rate of usage demands, voltages, power factor and reactive power used etc.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] They can also support time-of-day billing, for example, recording the amount of energy used during on-peak and off-peak hours.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The meter has a power supply, a metering engine, a processing and communication engine (i.e. a microcontroller), and other add-on modules such as a real time clock (RTC), a liquid crystal display, infra red communication ports/modules and so on.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The metering engine is given the voltage and current inputs and has a voltage reference, samplers and quantisers followed by an analog to digital conversion section to yield the digitised equivalents of all the inputs.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] These inputs are then processed using a digital signal processor to calculate the various metering parameters.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The largest source of long-term errors in the meter is drift in the preamp, followed by the precision of the voltage reference.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Both of these vary with temperature as well, and vary wildly when meters are outdoors.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Characterising and compensating for these is a major part of meter design.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The processing and communication section has the responsibility of calculating the various derived quantities from the digital values generated by the metering engine.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] This also has the responsibility of communication using various protocols and interface with other addon modules connected as slaves to it.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] RTC and other add-on modules are attached as slaves to the processing and communication section for various input/output functions.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] On a modern meter most if not all of this will be implemented inside the microprocessor, such as the RTC, LCD controller, temperature sensor, memory and analog to digital converters.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Remote meter reading is a practical example of telemetry.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] It saves the cost of a human meter reader and the resulting mistakes, but it also allows more measurements, and remote provisioning.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Many smart meters now include a switch to interrupt or restore service.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Historically, rotating meters could report their metered information remotely, using a pair of electrical contacts attached to a *KYZ* line.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] A **KYZ interface** is a Form C contact supplied from the meter.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In a KYZ interface, the Y and Z wires are switch contacts, shorted to K for a measured amount of energy.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] When one contact closes the other opens to provide count accuracy security.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Each contact change of state is considered one pulse.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The frequency of pulses indicates the power demand.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The number of pulses indicates energy metered.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] When incorporated into an electromechanical meter, the relay changes state with each full or half rotation of the meter disc.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] KYZ outputs were historically attached to "totaliser relays" feeding a "totaliser" so that many meters could be read all at once in one place.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] KYZ outputs are also the classic way of attaching electricity meters to programmable logic controllers, HVACs or other control systems.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Some modern meters also supply a contact closure that warns when the meter detects a demand near a higher electricity tariff, to improve demand side management.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] EN 62053-31 (formerly DIN 43864) defines the **S0 interface**, which is a galvanically isolated open collector output.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Voltage and current are limited to 27 V and 27 mA, respectively.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Each metered amount of electrical energy produces one impulse with a length of 32-100 ms.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The meter constant (pulses per kWh) is programmable on some meters, but often fixed to 1000-10000 pulses per kWh.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Other meters implement a similar pulse interface, but with an infrared LED instead of an electrical connection.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The interface is also used on other kinds of meters, like water meters.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Many meters designed for semi-automated reading have a serial port that communicates by infrared LED through the faceplate of the meter.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In some multi-unit buildings, a similar protocol is used, but in a wired bus using a serial current loop to connect all the meters to a single plug.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The plug is often near a more easily accessible point.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In the European Union, the most common infrared and protocol is "FLAG", a simplified subset of mode C of IEC 61107.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In the United States and Canada, the favored infrared protocol is ANSI C12.18.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Some industrial meters use protocols for programmable logic controllers, like Modbus or DNP3.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] One protocol proposed for this purpose is DLMS/COSEM which can operate over any medium, including serial ports.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The data can be transmitted by Zigbee, Wi-Fi, telephone lines or over the power lines themselves.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Some meters can be read over the internet.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Other more modern protocols are also becoming widely used, like OSGP (Open Smart Grid Protocol).
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Electronic meters now also use low-power radio, GSM, GPRS, Bluetooth, IrDA, as well as RS-485 wired link.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The meters can store the entire usage profiles with timestamps and relay them at the click of a button.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The demand readings stored with the profiles accurately indicate the load requirements of the customer.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] This load profile data is processed at the utilities for billing and planning purposes.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Large commercial and industrial premises may use electronic meters which record power usage in blocks of half an hour or less.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] This is because most electricity grids have demand surges throughout the day, and the power company may wish to give price incentives to large customers to reduce demand at these times.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] These demand surges often correspond to meal times or, famously, to advertisements interrupting popular television programmes, such as the TV pickup.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] A potentially powerful means to reduce household energy consumption is to provide convenient real-time feedback to users so they can change their energy using behaviour.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The display may indicate the power consumption over the week graphically.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] A study using a consumer-readable meter in 500 Ontario homes by *Hydro One* showed an average 6.5% drop in total electricity use when compared with a similarly sized control group.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] *Hydro One* subsequently offered free power monitors to 30,000 customers based on the success of the pilot.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Projects such as Google PowerMeter, take information from a smart meter and make it more readily available to users to help encourage conservation.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Plug-in electricity meters (or plug load meters) measure energy used by individual appliances.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] There are a variety of models available on the market today but they all work on the same basic principle.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The meter is plugged into an outlet, and the appliance to be measured is plugged into the meter.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Such meters can help in energy conservation by identifying major energy users, or devices that consume excessive standby power.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Web resources can also be used, if an estimate of the power consumption is enough for the research purposes.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] A power meter can often be borrowed from the local power authorities or a local public library.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Electricity retailers may wish to charge customers different tariffs at different times of the day to better reflect the costs of generation and transmission.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Since it is typically not cost effective to store significant amounts of electricity during a period of low demand for use during a period of high demand, costs will vary significantly depending on the time of day.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Some multiple tariff meters use different tariffs for different amounts of demand.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Domestic variable-rate meters generally permit two to three tariffs ("peak", "off-peak" and "shoulder") and in such installations a simple electromechanical time switch may be used.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Historically, these have often been used in conjunction with electrical storage heaters or hot water storage systems.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Multiple tariffs are made easier by time of use (TOU) meters which incorporate or are connected to a time switch and which have multiple registers.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Switching between the tariffs may happen via ripple control, or via a radio-activated switch.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In principle, a sealed time switch can also be used, but is considered more vulnerable to tampering to obtain cheaper electricity.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Radio-activated switching is common in the UK, with a nightly data signal sent within the longwave carrier of BBC Radio 4, 198 kHz.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The time of off-peak charging is usually seven hours between midnight and 7:00am GMT/BST, and this is designed to power storage heaters and immersion heaters.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In the UK, such tariffs are typically branded *Economy 7*, *White Meter* or *Dual-Rate*.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The popularity of such tariffs has declined in recent years, at least in the domestic market, because of the (perceived or real) deficiencies of storage heaters and the comparatively much lower cost of natural gas per kWh (typically a factor of 3-5 times lower).
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Nevertheless, a sizeable number of properties do not have the option of gas, with many in rural areas being outside the gas supply network, and others being expensive upfront to upgrade to a radiator system.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] An Economy 10 meter is also available, which gives 10 hours of cheap off-peak electricity spread out over three timeslots throughout a 24-hour period.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] This allows multiple top-up boosts to storage heaters, or a good spread of times to run a wet electric heating system on a cheaper electricity rate.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Most meters using *Economy 7* switch the entire electricity supply to the cheaper rate during the 7 hour night time period, not just the storage heater circuit.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The downside of this is that the daytime rate per kWh is significantly higher, and that standing charges are sometimes higher.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] For example, as of July 2017, normal ("single rate") electricity costs 17.14p per kWh in the London region on the standard default tariff for EDF Energy (the post-privatisation incumbent electricity supplier in London), with a standing charge of 18.90p per day.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The equivalent Economy 7 costs are 21.34p per kWh during the peak usage period with 7.83p per kWh during the off-peak usage period, and a standing charge of 18.90p per day.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Timer switches installed on washing machines, tumble dryers, dishwashers and immersion heaters may be set so that they only switch on during the off-peak usage period.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Smart meters go a step further than simple AMR (automatic meter reading).
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] They offer additional functionality including a real-time or near real-time reads, power outage notification, and power quality monitoring.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] They allow price setting agencies to introduce different prices for consumption based on the time of day and the season.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Another type of smart meter uses nonintrusive load monitoring to automatically determine the number and type of appliances in a residence, how much energy each uses and when.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] This meter is used by electric utilities to do surveys of energy use.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] It eliminates the need to put timers on all of the appliances in a house to determine how much energy each uses.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The standard business model of electricity retailing involves the electricity company billing the customer for the amount of energy used in the previous month or quarter.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In some countries, if the retailer believes that the customer may not pay the bill, a prepayment meter may be installed.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] This requires the customer to make advance payment before electricity can be used.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] If the available credit is exhausted then the supply of electricity is cut off by a relay.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In the UK, mechanical prepayment coin meters used to be common, both in private rented accommodation and residential customers of the electricity boards, the nationalised electricity sector.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Disadvantages of these included the need for regular visits to remove the cash, and risk of theft of the cash in the meters by both customers and burglars.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The first automated pre-payment meters were introduced by London Electricity, in conjunction with the Schlumberger Metering based in Felixstowe, UK.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] They were initially called Key Meters and later renamed Budget Meters.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] They avoided the 60,000 disconnections for non-payment per annum and the many disadvantages of cash prepayment.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] They were also popular with customers who wanted a convenient payment method, especially in short term tenancies.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Well over 1 million such meters were installed across the UK in the first few years after introduction.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Modern solid-state electricity meters, in conjunction with smart cards, have removed these disadvantages and such meters are commonly used for customers considered to be a poor credit risk.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In the UK, customers can use organisations such as the Post Office Limited or PayPoint network, where rechargeable tokens (Quantum cards for natural gas, or plastic "keys" for electricity) can be loaded with whatever money the customer has available.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In Indonesia, Northern Ireland, South Africa and Sudan, prepaid meters are recharged by entering a unique, encoded twenty digit number using a keypad.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] This makes the tokens, which may be electronically delivered or printed on a slip of paper at point of purchase, very cheap to produce.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Around the world, experiments are going on, especially in developing countries, to test pre-payment systems.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In some cases, prepayment meters have not been accepted by customers.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] There are various groups, such as the Standard Transfer Specification (STS) association, which promote common standards for prepayment metering systems across manufacturers.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Prepaid meters using the STS standard are used in many countries.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Time of Day metering (TOD), also known as Time of Usage (TOU) or Seasonal Time of Day (SToD), metering involves dividing the day, month and year into tariff slots and with higher rates at peak load periods and low tariff rates at off-peak load periods.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] While this can be used to automatically control usage on the part of the customer (resulting in automatic load control), it is often simply the customer's responsibility to control his own usage or pay accordingly (voluntary load control).
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] This also allows the utilities to plan their transmission infrastructure appropriately.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] TOD metering normally splits rates into an arrangement of multiple segments including on-peak, off-peak, mid-peak or shoulder, and critical peak.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] A typical arrangement is a peak occurring during the day (non-holiday days only), such as from 1 pm to 9 pm Monday through Friday during the summer and from 6:30 am to 12 noon and 5 pm to 9 pm during the winter.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] More complex arrangements include the use of critical peaks that occur during high demand periods.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The times of peak demand/cost will vary in different markets around the world.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Large commercial users can purchase power by the hour using either forecast pricing or real-time pricing.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Some utilities allow residential customers to pay hourly rates, such as in Illinois, which uses day ahead pricing.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Many electricity customers are installing their own electricity generating equipment, whether for reasons of economy, redundancy or environmental reasons.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] When a customer is generating more electricity than required for his own use, the surplus may be exported back to the power grid.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] This exported energy may be accounted for in the simplest case by the meter running backwards during periods of net export, thus reducing the customer's recorded energy usage by the amount exported.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] This in effect results in the customer being paid for his/her exports at the full retail price of electricity.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Unless equipped with a ratchet or equivalent, a standard meter will accurately record power flow in each direction by simply running backwards when power is exported.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Where allowed by law, utilities maintain a profitable margin between the price of energy delivered to the consumer and the rate credited for consumer-generated energy that flows back to the grid.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Lately, upload sources typically originate from renewable sources (e.g., wind turbines, photovoltaic cells), or gas or steam turbines, which are often found in cogeneration systems.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Another potential upload source that has been proposed is plug-in hybrid car batteries (vehicle-to-grid power systems).
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] This requires a "smart grid," which includes meters that measure electricity via communication networks that require remote control and give customers timing and pricing options.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The location of an electricity meter varies with each installation.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Possible locations include on a utility pole serving the property, in a street-side cabinet (meter box) or inside the premises adjacent to the consumer unit / distribution board.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Electricity companies may prefer external locations as the meter can be read without gaining access to the premises but external meters may be more prone to vandalism.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Current transformers permit the meter to be located remotely from the current-carrying conductors.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] For example, a substation serving a single large customer may have metering equipment installed in a cabinet, without bringing heavy cables into the cabinet.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Since electrical standards vary in different regions, "customer drops" from the grid to the customer also vary depending on the standards and the type of installation.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] There are several common types of connections between a grid and a customer.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Each type has a different *metering equation.* Blondel's theorem states that for any system with N current-carrying conductors, that N-1 measuring elements are sufficient to measure electrical energy.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] This indicates that different metering is needed, for example, for a three-phase three-wire system than for a three-phase four-wire (with neutral) system.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In Europe, Asia, Africa and most other locations, single phase is common for residential and small commercial customers.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Single phase distribution is less-expensive, because one set of transformers in a substation normally serve a large area with relatively high voltages (usually 230 V) and no local transformers.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] These have a simple metering equation: Watts = volts x amps, with volts measured from the neutral to the phase wire.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In the United States, Canada, and parts of Central and South America similar customers are normally served by three-wire single phase.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Three-wire single-phase requires local transformers, as few as one per ten residences, but provides lower, safer voltages at the socket (usually 120 V), and provides two voltages to customers: neutral to phase (usually 120 V), and phase to phase (usually 240 V).
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Additionally, three-wire customers normally have neutral wired to the zero side of the generator's windings, which gives earthing that can be easily measured to be safe.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] These meters have a metering equation of Watts = 0.5 x volts x (amps of phase A − amps of phase B), with volts measured between the phase wires.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Industrial power is normally supplied as three phase power.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] There are two forms: three wire, or four wire with a system neutral.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In "three wire" or "three wire delta", there is no neutral but an earth ground is the safety ground.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The three phases have voltage only relative to each other.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] This distribution method has one fewer wire, is less expensive, and is common in Asia, Africa, and many parts of Europe.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In regions that mix residences and light industry, it is common for this to be the only distribution method.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] A meter for this type normally measures two of the windings relative to the third winding, and adds the watts.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] One disadvantage of this system is that if the safety earth fails, it is difficult to discover this by direct measurement, because no phase has a voltage relative to earth.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In the four-wire three-phase system, sometimes called "four-wire wye", the safety ground is connected to a neutral wire that is physically connected to the zero-voltage side of the three windings of the generator or transformer.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Since all power phases are relative to the neutral in this system, if the neutral is disconnected, it can be directly measured.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In the United States, the National Electrical Code requires neutrals to be of this type.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In this system, power meters measure and sum all three phases relative to the neutral.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In North America, it is common for electricity meters to plug into a standardised socket outdoors, on the side of a building.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] This allows the meter to be replaced without disturbing the wires to the socket, or the occupant of the building.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Some sockets may have a bypass while the meter is removed for service.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The amount of electricity used without being recorded during this small time is considered insignificant when compared to the inconvenience which might be caused to the customer by cutting off the electricity supply.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Most electronic meters in North America use a serial protocol, ANSI C12.18.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In many other countries the supply and load terminals are in the meter housing itself.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Cables are connected directly to the meter.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In some areas the meter is outside, often on a utility pole.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In others, it is inside the building in a niche.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] If inside, it may share a data connection with other meters.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] If it exists, the shared connection is often a small plug near the post box.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The connection is often EIA-485 or infrared with a serial protocol such as IEC 62056.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In 2014, networking to meters is rapidly changing.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The most common schemes seem to combine an existing national standard for data (e.g.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] ANSI C12.19 or IEC 62056) operating via the Internet Protocol with a small circuit board for powerline communication, or a digital radio for a mobile phone network, or an ISM band.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Electricity meters are required to register the energy consumed within an acceptable degree of accuracy.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Any significant error in the registered energy can represent a loss to the electricity supplier, or the consumer being over billed.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The accuracy is generally laid down in statute for the location in which the meter is installed.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Statutory provisions may also specify a procedure to be followed should the accuracy be disputed.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] For the United Kingdom, any installed electricity meter is required to accurately record the consumed energy, but it is permitted to under-read by 3.5%, or over-read by 2.5%.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Disputed meters are initially verified with a check meter operating alongside the disputed meter.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The final resort is for the disputed meter to be fully tested both in the installed location and at a specialist calibration laboratory.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Approximately 93% of disputed meters are found to be operating satisfactorily.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] A refund of electricity paid for, but not consumed (but not vice versa) will only be made if the laboratory is able to estimate how long the meter has been misregistering.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] This contrasts with gas meters where if a meter is found to be under reading, it is assumed that it has under read for as long as the consumer has had a gas supply through it.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Any refund due is limited to the previous six years.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Meters can be manipulated to make them under-register, effectively allowing power use without paying for it.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Power companies often install remote-reporting meters specifically to enable remote detection of tampering, and specifically to discover energy theft.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The change to smart power meters is useful to stop energy theft.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] When tampering is detected, the normal tactic, legal in most areas of the United States, is to switch the subscriber to a "tampering" tariff charged at the meter's maximum designed current.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] At US$0.095/kWh, a standard residential 50 A meter causes a legally collectible charge of about US$5,000.00 per month.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Meter readers are trained to spot signs of tampering, and with crude mechanical meters, the maximum rate may be charged each billing period until the tamper is removed, or the service is disconnected.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] A common method of tampering on mechanical disk meters is to attach magnets to the outside of the meter.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Strong magnets saturate the magnetic fields in the meter so that the motor portion of a mechanical meter does not operate.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Lower power magnets can add to the drag resistance of the internal disk resistance magnets.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Magnets can also saturate current transformers or power-supply transformers in electronic meters, though countermeasures are common.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Some combinations of capacitive and inductive load can interact with the coils and mass of a rotor and cause reduced or reverse motion.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] All of these effects can be detected by the electric company, and many modern meters can detect or compensate for them.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The owner of the meter normally secures the meter against tampering.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Revenue meters' mechanisms and connections are sealed.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Meters may also measure VAR-hours (the reflected load), neutral and DC currents (elevated by most electrical tampering), ambient magnetic fields, etc.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Even simple mechanical meters can have mechanical flags that are dropped by magnetic tampering or large DC currents.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Newer computerised meters usually have counter-measures against tampering.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] AMR (Automated Meter Reading) meters often have sensors that can report opening of the meter cover, magnetic anomalies, extra clock setting, glued buttons, inverted installation, reversed or switched phases etc.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Some tampers bypass the meter, wholly or in part.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Safe tampers of this type normally increase the neutral current at the meter.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Most split-phase residential meters in the United States are unable to detect neutral currents.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] However, modern tamper-resistant meters can detect and bill it at standard rates.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Disconnecting a meter's neutral connector is unsafe because shorts can then pass through people or equipment rather than a metallic ground to the generator or earth.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] A phantom loop connection via an earth ground is often much higher resistance than the metallic neutral connector.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Even if an earth ground is safe, metering at the substation can alert the operator to tampering.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Substations, inter-ties, and transformers normally have a high-accuracy meter for the area served.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Power companies normally investigate discrepancies between the total billed and the total generated, in order to find and fix power distribution problems.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] These investigations are an effective method to discover tampering.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Power thefts in the United States are often connected with indoor marijuana grow operations.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Narcotics detectives associate abnormally high power usage with the lighting such operations require.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Indoor marijuana growers aware of this are particularly motivated to steal electricity simply to conceal their usage of it.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Electricity meters are governed by various standards worldwide to ensure accuracy, reliability, and interoperability.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] These standards vary by region and are often based on national or international regulations.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Below are the key standards used in different regions.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In Europe, electricity meters are primarily regulated under the Measuring Instruments Directive (MID), established by the European Union.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] MID ensures that electricity meters meet specific technical and operational criteria for accurate billing.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] In the United States, the standards are developed by the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) and the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE).
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Following the deregulation of electricity supply markets in many countries, the company responsible for an electricity meter may not be obvious.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Depending on the arrangements in place, the meter may be the property of the meter Operator, electricity distributor, the retailer or for some large users of electricity the meter may belong to the customer.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The company responsible for reading the meter may not always be the company which owns it.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Meter reading is now sometimes subcontracted and in some areas the same person may read gas, water and electricity meters at the same time.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] The introduction of advanced meters in residential areas has produced additional privacy issues that may affect ordinary customers.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] These meters are often capable of recording energy usage every 15, 30 or 60 minutes.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Some meters have one or two IR LEDs on the front: one used for testing and which acts as the equivalent of the timing mark on the older mechanical meters and the other as part of a two-way IR communications port for reading / programming the meter.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] These IR LEDs are visible with some night vision viewers and certain video cameras that are capable of sensing IR transmissions.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] These can be used for surveillance, revealing information about peoples' possessions and behaviour.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] For instance, it can show when the customer is away for extended periods.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] Nonintrusive load monitoring gives even more detail about what appliances people have and their living and use patterns.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/electricity-meter] A more detailed and recent analysis of this issue was performed by the Illinois Security Lab.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/maximum-demand-indicator] MDI is often available as a built-in feature of three phase energy meters.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/peak-load] Some utilities will charge customers based on their individual peak demand.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/peak-load] The highest demand during each month or even a single 15 to 30 minute period of highest use in the previous year may be used to calculate charges.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/peak-load] The renewable energy transition will include considerations for peak demand.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/peak-load] Electricity network is built to deal with the highest possible peak demand otherwise blackout may happen.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/peak-load] In Australia, demand tariff has three components: peak demand charge, energy charge and daily connection charge.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/peak-load] For example, for large customers (commercial, industrial or mixed of commercial/residential), the peak demand charge is based on the highest 30 minutes electricity consumption in a month; the energy charge is based on a month electricity consumption.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/peak-load] This type of demand tariff is gradually introduced to residential households and will be rolled out by 2020 in Queensland Australia.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/peak-load] How to manage electricity bills under demand tariff can be challenging.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/peak-load] The key solutions involve improving building efficiency and managing the operational settings of large power appliances.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/peak-load] Peak Demand depends on the demography, the economy, the weather, the climate, the season, the day of the week and other factors.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/peak-load] In industrialised regions of China or Germany, the peak demands mostly occur in day time.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/peak-load] However, in more service based economy such as Australia, the daily peak demands often occur in the late afternoon to early evening time (e.g.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/peak-load] Residential and commercial electricity demand contributes a lot to this type of network peak demand.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/peak-load] Peak demand is considered to be the opposite to off-peak hours when power demand is usually low.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/peak-load] Sometimes, there are 3 time-of-use zones: peak, shoulder and offpeak.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/peak-load] Shoulder is often the time between peak and offpeak in weekdays.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/peak-load] Weekends are often just peak and offpeak in terms of managing electricity loads for the network.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/peak-load] Peak demand may exceed the maximum supply levels that the electrical power industry can generate, resulting in power outages and load shedding.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/peak-load] This often occurs during heat waves when use of air conditioners and powered fans raises the rate of energy consumption significantly.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/peak-load] During a shortage authorities may request the public to curtail their energy use and shift it to a non-peak period.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/peak-load] Power stations specifically constructed for providing power to electrical grids for peak demand are called peaking power plants or 'peakers'.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/peak-load] In general, Natural gas fueled power stations can be fired up rapidly and are therefore often utilized at peak demand times.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/peak-load] Combined cycle power plants can frequently provide power for peak demand, as well as run efficiently for baseload power.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/peak-load] Hydroelectric power and pumped storage type dams such as Carters Dam in the U.S. state of Georgia help to meet peak demand as well.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/peak-load] The chances that a wind farm will be unable to meet peak demand are greater than for a fossil-fueled power station, due to the ability to store liquid fuels for use during peak demand.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/peak-load] Solar power's peak output often naturally coincides with daytime peaks of usage due to air conditioning.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] A **short circuit** (sometimes abbreviated to "short" or "s/c") is an electrical circuit that allows an electric current to travel along an unintended path with no or very low electrical impedance.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] This results in an excessive current flowing through the circuit.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] The opposite of a short circuit is an open circuit, which is an infinite resistance (or very high impedance) between two nodes.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] A short circuit is an abnormal connection between two nodes of an electric circuit intended to be at different voltages.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] This results in a current limited only by the Thévenin equivalent resistance of the rest of the network which can cause circuit damage, overheating, fire or explosion.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] Although usually the result of a fault, there are cases where short circuits are caused intentionally, for example, for the purpose of voltage-sensing crowbar circuit protectors.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] In circuit analysis, a *short circuit* is defined as a connection between two nodes that forces them to be at the same voltage.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] In an 'ideal' short circuit, this means there is no resistance and thus no voltage drop across the connection.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] In real circuits, the result is a connection with almost no resistance.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] In such a case, the current is limited only by the resistance of the rest of the circuit.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] A common type of short circuit occurs when the positive and negative terminals of a battery or a capacitor are connected with a low-resistance conductor, like a wire.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] With a low resistance in the connection, a high current will flow, causing the delivery of a large amount of energy in a short period of time.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] A high current flowing through a battery can cause a rapid increase of temperature, potentially resulting in an explosion with the release of hydrogen gas and electrolyte (an acid or a base), which can burn tissue and cause blindness or even death.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] Overloaded wires will also overheat causing damage to the wire's insulation, or starting a fire.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] In electrical devices, unintentional short circuits are usually caused when a wire's insulation breaks down, or when another conducting material is introduced, allowing charge to flow along a different path than the one intended.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] In mains circuits, short circuits may occur between two phases, between a phase and neutral or between a phase and earth (ground).
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] Such short circuits are likely to result in a very high current and therefore quickly trigger an overcurrent protection device.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] However, it is possible for short circuits to arise between neutral and earth conductors and between two conductors of the same phase.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] Such short circuits can be dangerous, particularly as they may not immediately result in a large current and are therefore less likely to be detected.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] Possible effects include unexpected energisation of a circuit presumed to be isolated.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] To help reduce the negative effects of short circuits, power distribution transformers are deliberately designed to have a certain amount of leakage reactance.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] The leakage reactance (usually about 5 to 10% of the full load impedance) helps limit both the magnitude and rate of rise of the fault current.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] A short circuit may lead to formation of an electric arc.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] The arc, a channel of hot ionized plasma, is highly conductive and can persist even after significant amounts of original material from the conductors have evaporated.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] Surface erosion is a typical sign of electric arc damage.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] Even short arcs can remove significant amounts of material from the electrodes.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] The temperature of the resulting electrical arc is very high (tens of thousands of degrees), causing the metal on the contact surfaces to melt, pool and migrate with the current, as well as to escape into the air as fine particulate matter.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] Within milliseconds, a short circuit can deliver a fault current that is hundreds or thousands of times higher than the normal operating current of the system.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] In an improper installation, the overcurrent from a short circuit may cause ohmic heating of the circuit parts with poor conductivity (faulty joints in wiring, faulty contacts in power sockets, or even the site of the short circuit itself).
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] Such overheating is a common cause of fires.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] An electric arc, if it forms during the short circuit, produces high amount of heat and can cause ignition of combustible substances as well.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] In industrial and utility distribution systems, dynamic forces generated by high short-circuit currents cause conductors to spread apart.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] Busbars, cables, and apparatus can be damaged by the forces generated in a short circuit.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] Damage from short circuits can be reduced or prevented by employing fuses, circuit breakers, or other overload protection, which disconnect the power in reaction to excessive current.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] Overload protection must be chosen according to the current rating of the circuit.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] Circuits for large home appliances require protective devices set or rated for higher currents than lighting circuits.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] Wire gauges specified in building and electrical codes are chosen to ensure safe operation in conjunction with the overload protection.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] An overcurrent protection device must be rated to safely interrupt the maximum prospective short-circuit current.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] In electronics, the ideal model (infinite gain) of an operational amplifier is said to produce a *virtual short circuit* between its input terminals because no matter what the output voltage is, the difference of potential between its input terminals is zero.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] If one of the input terminals is connected to the ground, then the other one is said to provide a virtual ground because its potential is (ideally) identical to that of the ground.
[src:maximum-demand-indicator/short-circuit] An ideal operational amplifier also has infinite input impedance, so unlike a real short circuit, no current flows between the terminals of the virtual short.
